The paper deals with algorithms for constructing a partition of space based on the zero-sets of polynomials, which is a problem in computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of the Borsuk-Ulam theorem and the focus on efficient algorithms suggest that the paper may also be relevant to computational topology (cs.DS) and algebraic geometry (cs.GC). The application to eliminating depth cycles among lines in 3-space suggests that the paper may also be relevant to computational geometry and computational topology (cs.CG, cs.SC), as well as robotics and control (cs.SY).
